WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:04.884
At T plus 0.678 seconds, the first warning appeared.

00:00:05.585 --> 00:00:07.691
It was smoke from the aft field joint

00:00:07.692 --> 00:00:10.358
of Challenger's right solid rocket booster.

00:00:11.300 --> 00:00:13.728
More smoke followed through the first two and

00:00:13.729 --> 00:00:15.070
a half seconds of flight.

00:00:15.071 --> 00:00:15.891
Then it stopped.

00:00:16.853 --> 00:00:20.140
For the next minute, Challenger looked like a launch.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:21.121
The vehicle climbed.

00:00:21.763 --> 00:00:22.885
The callouts continued.

00:00:23.506 --> 00:00:25.303
The machinery of the mission appeared to be

00:00:25.304 --> 00:00:26.551
doing what it had done before.

00:00:27.353 --> 00:00:29.056
But the accident had already begun.

00:00:29.818 --> 00:00:32.560
The visible catastrophe came later,

00:00:32.561 --> 00:00:34.948
about 73 seconds after liftoff.

00:00:34.968 --> 00:00:37.732
By then the public version could be told quickly.

00:00:37.733 --> 00:00:40.140
It was cold, the O-rings failed,

00:00:40.141 --> 00:00:42.279
and seven crew members died.

00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:44.140
That version is accurate.

00:00:44.921 --> 00:00:46.693
It is also too small to explain why

00:00:46.694 --> 00:00:48.085
launch was still allowed.

00:00:49.167 --> 00:00:51.163
The smoke is the better starting point because

00:00:51.164 --> 00:00:53.313
it separates the consequence from the beginning.

00:00:54.213 --> 00:00:56.597
At 73 seconds, the chain became public.

00:00:57.317 --> 00:01:00.262
At less than 1 second, the chain became physical.

00:01:01.042 --> 00:01:04.007
Before that, the chain had already been organizational.

00:01:04.008 --> 00:01:06.090
The harder question starts before ignition.

00:01:06.790 --> 00:01:09.829
How does a warning stay visible in records,

00:01:09.830 --> 00:01:12.952
inspections, memos, charts, and meetings,

00:01:12.953 --> 00:01:15.991
then arrive at the final decision two weeks

00:01:15.992 --> 00:01:17.426
to stop the machine?

00:01:18.346 --> 00:01:21.191
Challenger did not fail because the danger was invisible.

00:01:21.873 --> 00:01:23.743
It failed after a system learned how to

00:01:23.744 --> 00:01:26.080
keep flying with evidence that should have made

00:01:26.081 --> 00:01:26.840
flying harder.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:29.085
To understand how that happens,

00:01:29.086 --> 00:01:32.160
start with the promise the Shuttle system had

00:01:32.161 --> 00:01:32.727
to keep.

00:01:32.826 --> 00:01:36.657
Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo were built around singular

00:01:36.658 --> 00:01:38.858
missions, dedicated hardware,

00:01:38.859 --> 00:01:42.037
dedicated risk, dedicated public attention.

00:01:42.879 --> 00:01:45.081
The Shuttle was designed to break that model.

00:01:45.861 --> 00:01:48.651
Reusable, frequent, routine,

00:01:48.652 --> 00:01:51.549
less expedition, more airline.

00:01:52.349 --> 00:01:55.272
That promise shaped the organization around it.

00:01:55.608 --> 00:01:57.493
When a program promises routine,

00:01:57.494 --> 00:02:00.254
every delay starts to mean something different.

00:02:01.094 --> 00:02:04.083
A scrub is still an engineering decision,

00:02:04.084 --> 00:02:06.475
but it is also a schedule problem,

00:02:06.476 --> 00:02:09.037
a budget problem, a public problem,

00:02:09.038 --> 00:02:11.941
a problem that moves through contracts,

00:02:11.942 --> 00:02:15.443
payload windows, congressional expectations,

00:02:15.444 --> 00:02:17.835
and the reputation of the agency.

00:02:17.836 --> 00:02:21.535
NASA entered 1986 with an aggressive flight schedule

00:02:21.536 --> 00:02:24.165
and a system that had to justify itself

00:02:24.166 --> 00:02:25.645
through repetition.

00:02:26.567 --> 00:02:28.822
The Shuttle was not only a spacecraft,

00:02:28.823 --> 00:02:30.372
it was an operating model.

00:02:31.234 --> 00:02:34.022
The first thing to understand about Challenger is

00:02:34.023 --> 00:02:36.612
that the program was built to make spaceflight

00:02:36.613 --> 00:02:37.342
feel normal.

00:02:38.304 --> 00:02:39.925
Normal operation is useful.

00:02:40.687 --> 00:02:43.297
It is also dangerous when it teaches people

00:02:43.298 --> 00:02:46.776
to treat unresolved problems as background conditions.

00:02:47.092 --> 00:02:48.978
No one in this story needed to wake

00:02:48.979 --> 00:02:50.258
up wanting a disaster.

00:02:50.318 --> 00:02:53.160
That matters because the easy version turns the

00:02:53.161 --> 00:02:55.008
accident into a morality play.

00:02:55.889 --> 00:02:57.374
Bad people made bad choices,

00:02:57.375 --> 00:02:59.415
so better people would have stopped it.

00:03:00.337 --> 00:03:02.401
The record is harder than that.

00:03:02.669 --> 00:03:04.779
The system was full of people trying to

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:07.351
do their jobs inside a decision structure that

00:03:07.352 --> 00:03:09.395
kept lowering the force of warnings.

00:03:10.236 --> 00:03:12.379
Three pressures were running at the same time.

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:15.543
First, technical uncertainty.

00:03:16.264 --> 00:03:18.406
The Shuttle was enormously complex.

00:03:19.106 --> 00:03:22.635
Each flight produced new evidence about how hardware

00:03:22.636 --> 00:03:25.536
behaved in the real vehicle under real loads

00:03:25.537 --> 00:03:26.634
in real weather.

00:03:26.635 --> 00:03:29.277
That gap between design expectation and operating

00:03:29.278 --> 00:03:31.120
evidence is normal in engineering.

00:03:31.841 --> 00:03:33.924
What matters is how the gap gets handled.

00:03:35.004 --> 00:03:37.247
Second, schedule pressure.

00:03:38.028 --> 00:03:40.510
Delays did not move one item on one calendar.

00:03:41.111 --> 00:03:43.454
They shifted payloads, crews,

00:03:43.455 --> 00:03:46.157
customers, reviews, and promises.

00:03:46.998 --> 00:03:50.242
The cost of stopping was visible immediately.

00:03:50.243 --> 00:03:53.268
Third, institutional reputation.

00:03:54.250 --> 00:03:56.574
NASA was not only an engineering organization.

00:03:57.294 --> 00:04:00.009
It was a national symbol, a funding case,

00:04:00.010 --> 00:04:02.804
a Cold War instrument, and a public trust.

00:04:03.605 --> 00:04:06.150
These pressures met inside the same rooms.

00:04:06.871 --> 00:04:09.595
When they conflicted, the most flexible thing was

00:04:09.596 --> 00:04:10.698
often uncertainty.

00:04:11.419 --> 00:04:13.442
A technical concern could be reframed.

00:04:14.123 --> 00:04:15.605
It could be qualified.

00:04:15.606 --> 00:04:17.408
It could be moved to the next review.

00:04:18.110 --> 00:04:20.435
Schedule and reputation were harder to bend.

00:04:21.276 --> 00:04:23.040
So the practical standard drifted.

00:04:23.079 --> 00:04:26.760
The question became, keep flying unless the evidence

00:04:26.761 --> 00:04:29.050
against flying is overwhelming.

00:04:29.091 --> 00:04:31.036
That is very different from,

00:04:31.037 --> 00:04:33.792
do not fly unless the evidence for safety

00:04:33.793 --> 00:04:34.440
is clear.

00:04:35.543 --> 00:04:38.809
The difference showed up most clearly in one component.

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:41.280
The Shuttle used two solid rocket boosters for

00:04:41.281 --> 00:04:43.306
most of its thrust during the first two

00:04:43.307 --> 00:04:44.319
minutes of flight.

00:04:45.259 --> 00:04:48.064
Each booster was not built as one continuous piece.

00:04:48.766 --> 00:04:51.725
It was assembled from cylindrical segments,

00:04:51.726 --> 00:04:54.216
stacked and joined at the launch site.

00:04:54.217 --> 00:04:56.939
where the segments met, there was a field joint.

00:04:57.721 --> 00:05:00.441
Inside that joint, two rubber O-rings,

00:05:00.442 --> 00:05:03.408
a primary and a secondary, were supposed to

00:05:03.409 --> 00:05:06.293
seal the gap and keep hot combustion gases

00:05:06.294 --> 00:05:07.694
inside the booster.

00:05:08.557 --> 00:05:10.079
The joint had to seal quickly.

00:05:10.779 --> 00:05:13.085
Pressure inside the motor could distort the metal

00:05:13.086 --> 00:05:13.963
parts at ignition.

00:05:14.745 --> 00:05:17.339
The O-rings had to move into position fast

00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:19.932
enough to block hot gas before it escaped.

00:05:19.933 --> 00:05:22.336
Cold mattered because rubber does not respond the

00:05:22.337 --> 00:05:23.137
same way in cold.

00:05:24.038 --> 00:05:26.104
A seal that moves quickly when warm can

00:05:26.105 --> 00:05:27.783
respond more slowly when cold.

00:05:28.545 --> 00:05:31.528
In this joint, timing was not a detail.

00:05:32.329 --> 00:05:34.432
Timing was the safety margin.

00:05:35.254 --> 00:05:38.617
If the seals failed, there was no graceful backup.

00:05:39.298 --> 00:05:42.185
Hot gas could burn through the booster casing,

00:05:42.186 --> 00:05:44.109
reach surrounding structure,

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:46.848
and turn a local leak into a vehicle failure.

00:05:47.048 --> 00:05:49.952
The o-ring problem had been showing itself before Challenger.

00:05:50.915 --> 00:05:53.860
Post-flight inspections found erosion on the primary seal.

00:05:54.641 --> 00:05:56.632
In some cases, gas had blown past it

00:05:56.633 --> 00:05:58.829
and left evidence deeper in the joint.

00:05:59.831 --> 00:06:01.435
Engineers documented the damage.

00:06:02.036 --> 00:06:02.677
They measured it.

00:06:03.298 --> 00:06:04.079
They reported it.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:07.386
The dangerous part is what happened next.

00:06:07.687 --> 00:06:09.711
Because the mission succeeded,

00:06:09.712 --> 00:06:11.735
because the vehicles came home,

00:06:11.736 --> 00:06:14.659
damage could be processed as evidence that the

00:06:14.660 --> 00:06:16.983
system had tolerated the condition.

00:06:17.002 --> 00:06:20.120
A damaged component in a surviving system can

00:06:20.121 --> 00:06:21.269
be read two ways.

00:06:22.252 --> 00:06:25.028
One reading says, we were closer to failure

00:06:25.029 --> 00:06:27.265
than we should have been, so we stop

00:06:27.266 --> 00:06:29.964
and fix the condition before we repeat it.

00:06:29.965 --> 00:06:32.593
The other says, the vehicle survived,

00:06:32.594 --> 00:06:34.974
the margin held, and the risk can be

00:06:34.975 --> 00:06:38.012
carried while improvement work continues.

00:06:38.992 --> 00:06:41.107
The second reading became easier each time the

00:06:41.108 --> 00:06:42.355
Shuttle flew and returned.

00:06:43.036 --> 00:06:45.749
What had started as a serious anomaly gradually

00:06:45.750 --> 00:06:47.920
became part of the operating history.

00:06:48.601 --> 00:06:50.504
The O-ring warning did not disappear.

00:06:51.324 --> 00:06:51.805
It moved.

00:06:52.605 --> 00:06:55.111
That is how a warning can die inside

00:06:55.112 --> 00:06:58.309
a large organization, not through silence,

00:06:58.310 --> 00:06:59.951
through translation.

00:06:59.952 --> 00:07:02.718
It starts when an engineer sees something wrong.

00:07:03.459 --> 00:07:04.843
The data is specific.

00:07:05.444 --> 00:07:06.747
The language is uncomfortable.

00:07:07.369 --> 00:07:07.850
Erosion.

00:07:08.432 --> 00:07:08.892
Blow by.

00:07:09.553 --> 00:07:10.136
Heat effects.

00:07:10.877 --> 00:07:12.623
A seal that did not behave the way

00:07:12.624 --> 00:07:13.723
the design assumed.

00:07:14.685 --> 00:07:17.232
Precise evidence has force.

00:07:17.233 --> 00:07:19.454
then the evidence becomes a discussion item.

00:07:20.175 --> 00:07:22.842
It enters a meeting with dozens of other

00:07:22.843 --> 00:07:27.045
concerns, other anomalies, other systems, other deadlines.

00:07:27.846 --> 00:07:31.151
The context broadens and the urgency flattens.

00:07:31.791 --> 00:07:34.675
From there, the discussion becomes a judgment call.

00:07:35.416 --> 00:07:37.600
Does this affect the next flight?

00:07:37.601 --> 00:07:39.879
The answer depends on the question the room

00:07:39.880 --> 00:07:40.702
decides to ask.

00:07:41.463 --> 00:07:43.452
If the question is, can we prove this

00:07:43.453 --> 00:07:44.646
will cause a failure?

00:07:45.288 --> 00:07:46.509
The answer is usually no.

00:07:47.370 --> 00:07:49.993
Predicting a specific loss on a specific flight

00:07:49.994 --> 00:07:50.452
is hard.

00:07:51.213 --> 00:07:53.330
If the question is, can we prove this

00:07:53.331 --> 00:07:54.177
will not fail?

00:07:54.737 --> 00:07:55.958
The answer is also no.

00:07:56.738 --> 00:07:59.000
But the first question keeps the schedule alive.

00:07:59.961 --> 00:08:02.625
Then the judgment becomes a schedule decision.

00:08:02.626 --> 00:08:04.146
The language changes again.

00:08:04.968 --> 00:08:07.401
It is no longer mainly about erosion depth

00:08:07.402 --> 00:08:08.374
or sealing time.

00:08:09.154 --> 00:08:11.052
It is about whether there is enough cause

00:08:11.053 --> 00:08:11.499
to delay.

00:08:12.519 --> 00:08:13.802
Delay has a phone tree.

00:08:14.442 --> 00:08:15.425
Delay has cost.

00:08:16.146 --> 00:08:17.487
Delay has a visible owner.

00:08:18.490 --> 00:08:22.656
If the flight succeeds, the decision becomes precedent.

00:08:22.657 --> 00:08:24.678
we flew with that condition and came back.

00:08:25.641 --> 00:08:27.879
That fact starts to compete with the warning

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:28.786
that preceded it.

00:08:29.548 --> 00:08:31.891
This route ran more than once before Challenger.

00:08:32.653 --> 00:08:35.136
Each pass made the next one easier to defend.

00:08:35.937 --> 00:08:38.067
Engineers were not simply ignored,

00:08:38.068 --> 00:08:40.623
they were often heard, then absorbed into a

00:08:40.624 --> 00:08:43.179
process that had learned how to carry their

00:08:43.180 --> 00:08:44.812
concern without stopping.

00:08:44.813 --> 00:08:48.235
Months before Challenger, Roger Boisjoly warned that a

00:08:48.236 --> 00:08:51.584
similar field joint problem could lead to catastrophe

00:08:51.585 --> 00:08:54.205
of the highest order and loss of human life.

00:08:55.306 --> 00:08:57.469
That memo did not come from hindsight.

00:08:58.309 --> 00:09:00.453
It came from inside the system,

00:09:00.454 --> 00:09:03.669
before the accident, from an engineer close to

00:09:03.670 --> 00:09:04.658
the hardware.

00:09:05.465 --> 00:09:07.675
The temperature pattern also had more weight than

00:09:07.676 --> 00:09:09.412
the launch night argument made it feel.

00:09:10.212 --> 00:09:12.586
When the full flight history was framed one

00:09:12.587 --> 00:09:15.422
way, the cold weather signal could look debatable.

00:09:16.482 --> 00:09:19.521
When the full record was framed another way,

00:09:19.522 --> 00:09:23.134
cold O-ring distress became much harder to dismiss.

00:09:24.015 --> 00:09:27.112
A chart can contain real information and still

00:09:27.113 --> 00:09:30.527
weaken the warning if it frames the wrong question.

00:09:30.642 --> 00:09:33.335
Richard Feynman's later appendix named the broader

00:09:33.336 --> 00:09:34.192
danger plainly.

00:09:34.934 --> 00:09:37.501
Previous success can become misleading evidence.

00:09:38.404 --> 00:09:40.233
A survived flight can show that the vehicle

00:09:40.234 --> 00:09:40.792
got through.

00:09:40.812 --> 00:09:43.589
It does not prove the risk was safe

00:09:43.590 --> 00:09:44.482
to repeat.

00:09:45.086 --> 00:09:48.280
By January 1986, Challenger was not facing a

00:09:48.281 --> 00:09:49.230
new problem.

00:09:49.991 --> 00:09:52.073
The program had evidence of o-ring distress.

00:09:52.794 --> 00:09:53.995
It had temperature concern.

00:09:54.636 --> 00:09:55.376
It had waivers.

00:09:55.937 --> 00:09:56.678
It had memos.

00:09:57.259 --> 00:09:59.120
It had a known field joint problem.

00:09:59.782 --> 00:10:02.217
It had a launch system that kept treating

00:10:02.218 --> 00:10:04.365
survival as part of the safety case.

00:10:04.385 --> 00:10:06.428
Then the weather turned that old problem into

00:10:06.429 --> 00:10:07.288
a launch decision.

00:10:08.169 --> 00:10:10.932
January 27th, 1986.

00:10:11.994 --> 00:10:15.076
Less than 24 hours before the scheduled launch.

00:10:15.243 --> 00:10:18.324
A teleconference connected NASA's Marshall Space

00:10:18.325 --> 00:10:20.616
Flight Center, Kennedy Space Center,

00:10:20.617 --> 00:10:23.625
and Morton Thyacol, the contractor that built the

00:10:23.626 --> 00:10:25.058
solid rocket boosters.

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:28.083
The subject was temperature.

00:10:29.044 --> 00:10:32.264
Forecasts and engineering estimates pointed to launch

00:10:32.265 --> 00:10:35.416
conditions far colder than prior Shuttle experience.

00:10:35.436 --> 00:10:39.461
The launch temperature would be about 36 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:10:39.462 --> 00:10:42.695
The right aft field joint was estimated colder,

00:10:42.696 --> 00:10:44.796
around 28 degrees Fahrenheit,

00:10:44.797 --> 00:10:46.413
plus or minus 5 degrees.

00:10:47.274 --> 00:10:49.997
Thiokol engineers were concerned because cold could

00:10:49.998 --> 00:10:52.055
slow the O-rings at the exact moment they

00:10:52.056 --> 00:10:52.842
needed to seal.

00:10:53.984 --> 00:10:55.427
Their recommendation was clear.

00:10:56.248 --> 00:10:59.432
Do not launch below 53 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:11:00.153 --> 00:11:02.594
That number mattered because it was tied to

00:11:02.595 --> 00:11:05.578
the lowest relevant prior experience they believed

00:11:05.579 --> 00:11:06.663
they could defend.

00:11:06.998 --> 00:11:08.580
NASA managers pushed back.

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:12.323
In a technical review, pushback can be necessary.

00:11:13.164 --> 00:11:14.993
The danger was the standard that began to

00:11:14.994 --> 00:11:15.746
govern the room.

00:11:16.687 --> 00:11:17.708
The question drifted.

00:11:18.691 --> 00:11:20.491
Show that this is safe to fly.

00:11:21.192 --> 00:11:23.174
Became prove that it will fail.

00:11:24.196 --> 00:11:26.239
That shift reversed the burden of proof.

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:30.322
Instead of requiring evidence that launch was safe,

00:11:30.323 --> 00:11:33.346
The process demanded evidence that failure was certain.

00:11:34.346 --> 00:11:37.049
Engineering evidence usually does not arrive that way.

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:39.726
It arrives as a missing margin,

00:11:39.727 --> 00:11:41.854
a condition outside experience,

00:11:41.855 --> 00:11:44.590
a trend with enough signal to matter before

00:11:44.591 --> 00:11:47.022
the catastrophe supplies certainty.

00:11:47.741 --> 00:11:50.184
The engineers had evidence of risk.

00:11:50.205 --> 00:11:52.086
They did not have an equation that converted

00:11:52.087 --> 00:11:54.068
temperature into guaranteed loss of vehicle.

00:11:54.710 --> 00:11:57.373
That absence became useful to the launch case.

00:11:57.774 --> 00:11:59.937
Theakol asked for an offline caucus.

00:12:00.677 --> 00:12:02.755
The caucus lasted far longer than the five

00:12:02.756 --> 00:12:04.061
minutes first requested.

00:12:04.761 --> 00:12:07.465
When they returned, the recommendation had changed.

00:12:08.205 --> 00:12:09.866
The new position was that the data was

00:12:09.867 --> 00:12:11.688
inconclusive and launch could proceed.

00:12:11.729 --> 00:12:13.870
The cold had not changed.

00:12:14.432 --> 00:12:16.153
The joint had not changed.

00:12:16.793 --> 00:12:18.596
The limits of the data had not changed.

00:12:19.255 --> 00:12:20.677
The decision frame changed.

00:12:21.578 --> 00:12:24.706
One instruction from that caucus still carries the

00:12:24.707 --> 00:12:25.942
shape of the moment.

00:12:26.192 --> 00:12:28.291
Jerry Mason told Bob Lund to take off

00:12:28.292 --> 00:12:31.229
his engineering hat and put on his management hat.

00:12:32.030 --> 00:12:34.057
No single phrase explains the disaster.

00:12:34.097 --> 00:12:37.047
No single person explains it either.

00:12:37.465 --> 00:12:39.852
The deeper fact is that the same process

00:12:39.853 --> 00:12:43.251
could take a specific engineering objection and return

00:12:43.252 --> 00:12:46.216
a launch recommendation from the same evidence.

00:12:46.897 --> 00:12:49.032
The launch eve reversal is dramatic,

00:12:49.033 --> 00:12:50.822
but it is not the whole failure.

00:12:51.582 --> 00:12:54.246
A warning also has to travel.

00:12:54.967 --> 00:12:57.928
It has to move from hardware to engineers,

00:12:57.929 --> 00:13:01.821
from engineers to managers, from contractors to NASA,

00:13:01.822 --> 00:13:04.867
from lower review levels to the people with

00:13:04.868 --> 00:13:06.982
authority to stop the launch.

00:13:06.983 --> 00:13:09.544
At each step, the signal can be compressed.

00:13:10.426 --> 00:13:12.936
Compression is normal in large programs,

00:13:12.937 --> 00:13:16.236
but when compression changes an active objection into

00:13:16.237 --> 00:13:18.459
a resolved item, the system has made a

00:13:18.460 --> 00:13:20.754
decision without naming it directly.

00:13:21.535 --> 00:13:23.138
Safety should have been a backstop.

00:13:23.857 --> 00:13:26.636
The Commission later criticized weak problem

00:13:26.637 --> 00:13:29.059
reporting, inadequate trend analysis,

00:13:29.060 --> 00:13:32.551
misrepresented criticality, and safety structures that

00:13:32.552 --> 00:13:35.545
did not give the concern enough independent force

00:13:35.546 --> 00:13:36.970
at the decisive points.

00:13:36.971 --> 00:13:39.958
People can care about safety while the way

00:13:39.959 --> 00:13:43.286
decisions are made still lets a warning arrive

00:13:43.287 --> 00:13:45.932
too late, too thin, or too resolved to

00:13:45.933 --> 00:13:47.041
change action.

00:13:48.142 --> 00:13:51.932
By launch morning, the warning had passed through

00:13:51.933 --> 00:13:54.369
hardware evidence, paperwork,

00:13:54.370 --> 00:13:57.888
meetings, waivers, charts, recommendation,

00:13:57.889 --> 00:14:00.595
caucus and management acceptance.

00:14:00.615 --> 00:14:02.996
At the end of that route, launch was

00:14:02.997 --> 00:14:03.817
still open.

00:14:04.101 --> 00:14:06.269
at 11:38 a.m.

00:14:07.133 --> 00:14:10.187
Eastern Standard Time on January 28,

00:14:10.188 --> 00:14:14.719
1986, Challenger launched from Kennedy Space Center.

00:14:15.289 --> 00:14:18.218
Within the first second, smoke appeared near the

00:14:18.219 --> 00:14:19.576
right aft field joint.

00:14:20.297 --> 00:14:22.381
The primary o-ring had not sealed the way

00:14:22.382 --> 00:14:23.301
it needed to seal.

00:14:24.121 --> 00:14:27.147
The secondary o-ring, affected by cold and joint

00:14:27.148 --> 00:14:29.730
movement, had not saved the joint in time.

00:14:30.591 --> 00:14:32.905
The smoke continued through roughly T plus two

00:14:32.906 --> 00:14:33.855
and a half seconds.

00:14:34.635 --> 00:14:35.496
Then it disappeared.

00:14:36.339 --> 00:14:39.234
The commission considered that combustion residue may

00:14:39.235 --> 00:14:41.144
have temporarily sealed the breach.

00:14:41.226 --> 00:14:43.426
For a short time, the vehicle could look

00:14:43.427 --> 00:14:46.092
normal while the failure chain remained alive.

00:14:46.994 --> 00:14:49.694
That temporary quiet is one of the clearest

00:14:49.695 --> 00:14:51.119
details in the record.

00:14:52.100 --> 00:14:54.469
The physical system did what the organization had

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:55.484
been doing for years.

00:14:56.325 --> 00:15:00.227
A sign of breach appeared, an explanation arrived,

00:15:00.228 --> 00:15:01.951
and flight continued.

00:15:01.952 --> 00:15:04.576
Around 58 to 59 seconds into flight,

00:15:04.577 --> 00:15:06.676
flame became visible again.

00:15:06.696 --> 00:15:09.565
Hot gas from the right booster began damaging

00:15:09.566 --> 00:15:13.341
surrounding structure, including the external tank area.

00:15:14.302 --> 00:15:16.260
At approximately 73 seconds,

00:15:16.261 --> 00:15:17.905
Challenger broke apart.

00:15:18.866 --> 00:15:22.108
Francis Dick Scoby, Michael Smith,

00:15:22.109 --> 00:15:25.242
Judith Resnick, Ellison Onizuka,

00:15:25.243 --> 00:15:28.159
Ronald McNair, Gregory Jarvis,

00:15:28.160 --> 00:15:31.077
and Krista McAuliffe were lost.

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:33.333
The visible failure lasted seconds.

00:15:34.115 --> 00:15:36.578
The invisible one had been accumulating for years.

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:40.785
What came next was the question every institution fears.

00:15:41.547 --> 00:15:44.091
How did this happen when the evidence already existed?

00:15:45.052 --> 00:15:47.868
President Reagan appointed the Rogers Commission,

00:15:47.869 --> 00:15:49.340
chaired by William Rogers.

00:15:50.381 --> 00:15:52.609
Richard Feynman was one of its members,

00:15:52.610 --> 00:15:55.040
and his independent work became part of the

00:15:55.041 --> 00:15:57.133
public memory of the investigation.

00:15:57.518 --> 00:15:59.709
The physical cause was direct,

00:15:59.710 --> 00:16:02.659
failure of the seal in the right booster's

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:05.104
aft field joint, hot gas escaping,

00:16:05.105 --> 00:16:07.464
damage to the external tank area,

00:16:07.465 --> 00:16:08.981
and vehicle breakup.

00:16:09.864 --> 00:16:13.029
The commission did not stop at the physical cause,

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:15.832
It found a flawed launch decision process.

00:16:16.594 --> 00:16:18.056
It found communication failures.

00:16:18.836 --> 00:16:21.750
It found that crucial information about O-ring

00:16:21.751 --> 00:16:23.716
history, temperature concern,

00:16:23.717 --> 00:16:26.994
and continuing engineering opposition did not reach

00:16:26.995 --> 00:16:29.834
key decision makers with the force and clarity

00:16:29.835 --> 00:16:30.490
it needed.

00:16:30.510 --> 00:16:33.757
The people closest to the hardware had the

00:16:33.758 --> 00:16:36.076
sharpest version of the risk.

00:16:36.096 --> 00:16:38.745
The people with the authority to stop launch

00:16:38.746 --> 00:16:40.822
received a softened version of it.

00:16:40.955 --> 00:16:43.870
The commission described the immediate failure,

00:16:43.871 --> 00:16:45.813
the part, the launched decision,

00:16:45.814 --> 00:16:49.145
and the communication system that softened the warning.

00:16:50.086 --> 00:16:52.915
Diane Vaughan later named the larger pattern,

00:16:52.916 --> 00:16:54.873
the normalization of deviance.

00:16:55.833 --> 00:16:58.598
A deviation from expected performance becomes normal

00:16:58.599 --> 00:17:00.581
because the system keeps surviving it.

00:17:01.501 --> 00:17:03.598
The phrase is useful because it does not

00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:04.806
require a conspiracy.

00:17:04.826 --> 00:17:09.392
It describes a slow adjustment in what feels acceptable.

00:17:09.727 --> 00:17:12.606
The line moves because each previous crossing did

00:17:12.607 --> 00:17:13.977
not end in catastrophe.

00:17:14.940 --> 00:17:17.940
Challenger is taught in engineering programs,

00:17:17.941 --> 00:17:21.541
business schools, and organizational behavior courses

00:17:21.542 --> 00:17:24.241
because the pattern is not limited to NASA.

00:17:24.458 --> 00:17:28.084
Repeated near misses create false confidence.

00:17:28.104 --> 00:17:31.310
Every time a system survives a close call,

00:17:31.311 --> 00:17:33.233
perceived risk can drop.

00:17:33.974 --> 00:17:36.519
The near miss gets counted as validation instead

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:37.140
of warning.

00:17:37.902 --> 00:17:39.964
Missing data gets mistaken for safety.

00:17:40.846 --> 00:17:43.207
No evidence of failure is not the same

00:17:43.208 --> 00:17:46.178
as evidence of no failure, especially when the

00:17:46.179 --> 00:17:49.301
dangerous condition has not really been tested.

00:17:49.302 --> 00:17:53.103
schedule pressure changes proof standards quietly no

00:17:53.104 --> 00:17:55.499
one has to announce that the bar has

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:58.226
moved the bar for stopping can rise inch

00:17:58.227 --> 00:18:02.275
by inch until only certainty of disaster justifies delay.

00:18:03.397 --> 00:18:06.345
Institutions reward continuity over interruption.

00:18:07.237 --> 00:18:09.252
The person who keeps the line moving is

00:18:09.253 --> 00:18:11.644
easier to celebrate than the person who stops

00:18:11.645 --> 00:18:14.037
it for a risk that might never become visible.

00:18:15.039 --> 00:18:16.765
Anomalies become background noise.

00:18:17.547 --> 00:18:20.277
The first time something unexpected happens,

00:18:20.278 --> 00:18:21.397
it gets attention.

00:18:21.682 --> 00:18:23.846
The fifth time, a tracking number.

00:18:24.866 --> 00:18:27.905
The tenth time, it starts to sound like

00:18:27.906 --> 00:18:29.615
how the system works.

00:18:29.634 --> 00:18:32.794
These behaviors appear wherever the cost of stopping

00:18:32.795 --> 00:18:36.165
is immediate, and the cost of continuing is statistical.

00:18:37.028 --> 00:18:40.759
Healthcare systems, financial systems,

00:18:40.760 --> 00:18:43.317
infrastructure, software.

00:18:43.318 --> 00:18:45.910
any organization that has to decide whether a

00:18:45.911 --> 00:18:48.707
warning is strong enough to interrupt momentum.

00:18:49.689 --> 00:18:51.551
Challenger did not invent this pattern.

00:18:52.313 --> 00:18:53.515
It made the pattern visible.

00:18:54.416 --> 00:18:56.921
Disasters rarely begin at the moment of impact.

00:18:57.662 --> 00:19:00.111
They begin when a system gets used to

00:19:00.112 --> 00:19:04.192
explaining away what it should have stopped to understand.

00:19:04.193 --> 00:19:06.675
Challenger was a long sequence of accommodations.

00:19:07.336 --> 00:19:08.912
Each one easier to defend than the whole

00:19:08.913 --> 00:19:09.820
chain would have been.

00:19:10.821 --> 00:19:12.989
The smoke at T plus 0.678 seconds is

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:16.128
why the story should not start with the explosion.

00:19:17.089 --> 00:19:19.113
The first visible warning was small.

00:19:19.953 --> 00:19:20.694
Then it vanished.

00:19:21.576 --> 00:19:23.858
For a while, everything looked normal.

00:19:24.721 --> 00:19:27.084
The same thing had already happened inside the organization.

00:19:28.045 --> 00:19:28.986
A warning appeared.

00:19:29.527 --> 00:19:30.709
The system explained it.

00:19:31.288 --> 00:19:33.251
The launch continued.

00:19:33.252 --> 00:19:36.017
That is why the next case belongs beside Challenger.

00:19:36.718 --> 00:19:39.162
Therac-25 is not another space story.

00:19:39.883 --> 00:19:42.384
It is a smaller room, a medical machine,

00:19:42.385 --> 00:19:45.871
a software interface, and operators trying to explain

00:19:45.872 --> 00:19:48.979
errors the machine was not built to make visible.

00:19:48.980 --> 00:19:50.084
The form changes.

00:19:50.827 --> 00:19:51.791
The pattern does not.

00:19:52.515 --> 00:19:54.945
Confidence moves faster than verification.

00:19:56.030 --> 00:19:56.554
Next time.

00:19:57.175 --> 00:19:57.900
Therac-25.

00:19:58.141 --> 00:20:01.375
A medical machine that exposed what happens when

00:20:01.376 --> 00:20:05.161
software confidence outruns the evidence users can see.
